{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492535"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1093"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1093"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.03,0.06,0.22,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108529"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1093"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40524"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108529"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old woman presents with a one day history of upper abdominal pain. She has never had these symptoms before. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoporotic vertebral collapse. She otherwise enjoyed good health, with a normal appetite and maintains her weight. She is a reformed smoker and drinks three glasses of wine a week. She takes perindopril and paracetamol. On examination the only relevant clinical finding is tenderness in the right upper quadrant. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the oesophagus","Retrosternal goitre","Carcinoma of the bronchus","Aortic aneurysm","Para-oesophageal hernia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA 8 cm diameter structure is visible immediately posterior to the heart and anterior to the aorta. It contains solid material and gas bubbles. This is a large \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E and is probably an incidental finding and not related to the patient\u0027s current symptoms. Sliding and para-oesophageal hernias are very common in the older population and whilst they can be associated with symptoms of gastro-oesophageal reflux and early satiety, they can often be incidental findings on chest X-ray or CT. It perhaps somewhat surprising that a hernial defect allowing most of the stomach into the chest can pass unnoticed by the patient. Whilst not shown on this slice, the oesophagus is to the right of the hernia, making it a para-oesophageal hernia. Otherwise it should be described as a sliding hernia. Here is a coronal view of the same hernia (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncidental radiological findings are common, particularly in patients over the age of 60. It is estimated that over 50% of this age group will have some sort of incidental finding. These include adrenal lesions, renal cysts, \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic aneurysms\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egoitres\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinomas of the bronchus or oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E can occasionally be picked up incidentally, these tumours usually make their presence known clinically before they are identified radiologically.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Para-oesophageal hernias are relatively common incidental findings on cross-sectional imaging."],"references":["Lumbreras B, Donat L, Hernandez-Aguado I. Incidental findings in imaging diagnostic tests: a systematic review. Br J Radiol 2010; 83:276-289."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1093"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18376"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21943"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18376"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49dd935d-284e-4549-a0c6-54d8142eb83b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49dd935d-284e-4549-a0c6-54d8142eb83b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":742,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"21943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21943"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g2df97v7UojQccpe9SxJk6BGgCIlEQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g2df97v7UojQccpe9SxJk6BGgCIlEQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":637,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-11T19:53:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T19:54:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1093"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/